AN OPERATIONAL RECONSTRUCTION OF LORENTZIAN MANIFOLDS:

Emergence of Spacetime Geometry from Causal Conditional Entropy and Quantum Error Correction

ABSTRACT

This thesis proposes a phenomenological framework for reconstructing (3+1)-dimensional Lorentzian manifolds from the causal entanglement structure of an underlying quantum system. We introduce Causal Conditional Entropy (CCE) as a dynamic extension of holographic entanglement entropy, encoding both spatial and temporal quantum correlations. The central conjecture posits a mapping between the Quantum Fisher Information Metric of boundary states and the emergent bulk spacetime metric via the relation $g_{\mu\nu} \propto (\det C)^{-1/d}C_{\mu\nu}$, where $C_{\mu\nu}$ is a causal correlation tensor derived from quantum field variations.

By grounding this emergent geometry in Quantum Error Correcting Codes (QECC), specifically topological stabilizer codes, we demonstrate a mechanism for the stability of classical spacetime against local quantum fluctuations—addressing the "reference state problem" that plagues many emergent gravity proposals. The framework predicts Ricci flattening as a necessary condition for a consistent emergent geometry, leading to a numerical verification protocol using simulated quantum systems. We implement this protocol on (1+1)D Ising model data, showing preliminary evidence for metric emergence that approximately satisfies vacuum Einstein equations within computational tolerance.

The work contributes to the "It from Qubit" paradigm by providing explicit, computable maps from quantum information to differential geometry, bridging concepts from AdS/CFT, tensor networks, and quantum information theory into a unified phenomenological framework for emergent spacetime.

